        <div class="slide active w-full max-w-4xl h-full flex-col items-center justify-center text-center bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-8">
            <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-bold text-gray-900">AP Calculus AB</h1>
            <p class="mt-4 text-2xl md:text-3xl text-indigo-600">Squeeze Theorem & Continuity</p>
            <p class="mt-8 text-lg text-gray-500">A presentation of examples.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 2: Squeeze Theorem Intuition -->
        <div class="slide w-full max-w-4xl h-full flex-col items-center justify-center text-center bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-8">
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-4">The Squeeze Theorem</h2>
            <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-600 max-w-2xl mb-6">
                <strong>The Idea:</strong> If we have a tricky function whose limit is hard to find, we can "squeeze" it between two other, simpler functions. If both of those outer functions approach the same limit at a certain point, the function squeezed between them must also approach that same limit.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-gray-600 max-w-2xl italic">
                <strong>Metaphor:</strong> Imagine you're walking between two friends who are holding your hands. If both of your friends walk through a doorway, you have no choice but to walk through that same doorway with them.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Slide 3: Squeeze Theorem Gallery -->
        <div class="slide w-full max-w-4xl h-full flex-col items-center justify-center bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-8">
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Example: Squeeze Theorem</h3>
            <!-- Main Image Display -->
            <img id="squeeze-main" src="figures/KA_squeeze_theorem_question.png" alt="Squeeze Theorem Example" class="max-w-full h-auto rounded-lg shadow-md mb-4" style="max-height: 400px;">
            <!-- Thumbnails -->
            <div class="flex gap-2 md:gap-4">
